        Three charged in fatal shooting by ATF agent in St. Louis
    


BY ROBERT PATRICK • rpatrick@post-dispatch.com > 314-621-5154











Robert Patrick


























Aug 31, 2012

 (…)























































































Myron Pollard
 


Joel Currier


























Authorities investigate a shooting scene involving ATF agents at Grand Boulevard and Iron Street in St. Louis on Wednesday, Aug. 29, 2012. Photo by Joel Currier, jcurrier@post-dispatch.com
 


Joel Currier








































































ST. LOUIS • St. Louis prosecutors charged three St. Louis men Friday with second-degree murder after one of their accomplices in a planned robbery was fatally shot by a federal agent.
Demitrius Creighton, 17, Arlando Austin Quarles, 22, and Lorenzo Tate, 17, were planning a drug robbery when they met with an undercover agent of the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives in the 3600 block of Iron Street on Wednesday at 11:17 a.m., according to charging documents. The men were armed at the time.
When the agent ordered them out of the car, Creighton, who was driving, put the car in reverse and sped towards another agent, who fired at the men, documents say.

Myron Pollard, 18, was hit and died the next day.
In addition to the murder charges, Quarles and Tate were charged with attempted robbery and Creighton with second-degree assault on a law enforcement officer.
Police and the ATF have referred questions to the U.S. Attorney's office, which is also considering charges. Tate and Creighton, whose first name is also spelled Damitrius in court documents, are considered adults in state court but juveniles in the federal system, and federal prosecutors have not charged a juvenile here in 25 years, officials said.

Quarles has two pending felony assault cases from earlier this year, was sentenced last year to 30 days in jail for a misdemeanor marijuana possession charge and got probation this year for charges of third-degree assault and a charge of trafficking of crack cocaine.
Tate has pending charges alleging that police caught him with  crack and marijuana in April.

While a juvenile, Tate spent time in a juvenile facility for a robbery charge.
Creighton has no other pending charges but also spent time in a juvenile facility after two separate charges of unlawful use of a weapon.

EDITOR'S NOTE: An earlier version of this story had an incorrect listing of charges. This version has been updated.



















        

        
